Weight reduction surgery could be useful for mildly obese diabetics
The benefits of weight reduction surgery for people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could be maintained for at least five years according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether mild-obesit diabetics live longer after weight loss surgery than those who pursue neurgic treatments.
"It takes a long time to centralize mortality data," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, who wrote an article on the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Operations for weight loss, called bariatric surgery, use different methods to narrow the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proved effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been performed on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) 35 or higher.
BMI, a weight measurement unit relative to height, is considered normal within the range 18,5-24,9.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that one person is overweight and people with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate the BMI by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers from the General Min-Sheng Hospital in Taiwan used close data after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - bypass gastric and gastrectomy in manson - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes to people with mild obesity.
Mean BMI in patients who underwent surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 to the end of the fifth year of the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received neurgic treatments against diabetes remained at almost the same level, namely 29.
Of those who underwent surgery, diabetes was completely cured at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes was completely cured at only 1% and partly at only 2% of subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
Researchers also monitored the blood level of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects the level of blood glucose over time.
Researchers write that the optimal level of haemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
Following surgery, the average haemoglobin level of A1c decreased from approximately 9% to about 6%.
However, in the group treated by medical methods, it remained at about 8%.
However, this improved glycaemic control - reflected by improved haemoglobin levels A1c - has not reduced mortality to five years, according to chief researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared with the gastrectomy group in manson, the bypass surgical intervention group lost more weight (18.7 than 14.2 kg), recorded more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1% compared to 2.1%) and presented a higher probability of complete remission of diabetes (46.9% compared to 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study performed on people with high weight in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, from Arizona University, Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese individuals who underwent bariatric surgery presented a probability of approximately 29% less to die after 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit to patients who underwent surgery, Blackstone said it is an optimistic aspect for people with BMI under 35 who are interested in the procedure.
“This is the point where this work is critical because it says that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group,” she says, without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking the weight seriously then the patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
“I think we wait too long until we urge people to take this aspect seriously,” she said.
I think once they've accumulated these genetic changes that shorten their bodies by predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it's extremely hard to get back to normal.
